Is the Series Stationary?¶

Use the notation NOK, when operating on Norwegian kroner, and let lNOK mean log(NOK). Investigate using plots and the DF test whether the $NOK$ is stationary. Use your knowledge of world events to give at leat one explanation of your finding.¶

print('ADF Statistic:%f' %adf[0])

p-value is:0.793805
ADF Statistic:-0.882116

Ideally, P-value should be less than 0.05. Small p-values suggest the data is stationary. Since we have high p-value, which implies that the NOK log price is not stationary.

From the knowledge of the world event, Norway Kroner has close relationship with the oil price now that Norway economy is heavily dependent on oil export. If we look into the oil price data as below, We can clearly see that the oil price has a negative relationship with Norwegian kroner. And it is well known that the price of oil is not stationary and its volatility has a heteroskedasticity property. The oil price went down significantly since a June 2014 to mid 2016, where the price was 115 USD a barrel around june and dropped to below 40 USD at the lowest. On the contrary, we can see the NOK price move in an opposite way with very high correlation. This means that the NOK is very likeley to follow non-stationary process with hetergoskedasticity property.

A dendrogram is a branching diagram that represents the relationships of similarity among a group of entities. Note that the Danish Krone is part of the European Exchange Rate Mechanism, aimed at reducing exchange rate volatility among EU nations. It pegs to the Euro at a ratio of 7.46 krone to one euro, and is required to stay within 2.25% of that level.

Two closest clusters are joined into the same cluster. As it is showns in the dendogram, besides the pair of DKK and EUR, CAD and NOK are more similar than others, which has 0.98 correlation coefficient. This is mainly because they are both very vulnerable to oil price as oil exporter. The next currency that shows close relationship to NOK is SEK, which is reasonble in that they share the border and their economy somewhat depend on natural resources. Moreover, since we know from the HW3 that CAD has a lower correlation with other currencies (DKK,HKD,SGD,CHF,EUR), we can safely say that the two most relavant currency to predict lNOK is CAD and SEK. And the next two are DKK and EUR.

Simply Trying Regression to Generate Signal¶

Suppose that we trade NOK with CAD and SEK. This gives rise to a regression


$lNOK=\gamma_1 lCAD + \gamma_2 lSEK + \epsilon$


We wish to implement a strategy along the lines of Question 2(b) of HW3. We trade with USD as basis currency, and we short the NOK when $\epsilon$ reaches a comparatively high value $highC$, and we go long the NOK when $\epsilon$ reaches a comparatively low value $lowC$.
Describe three strategies for this situation.

(i) The basic strategy

(ii) The reinforcing strategy

(iii) The reinforcing with a limit on the number of positions.

Simple Regression¶

gamma1 = 0.8345 (SEK) , gamma2 = -0.2891 (CAD)

$spread=lNOK-\gamma_{CAD}lCAD-\gamma_{SEK}lSEK=\epsilon$

  • When $\epsilon$ is > 0, $ lNOK > \gamma_{CAD}\cdot lCAD-\gamma_{SEK} \cdot lSEK$
  • When $\epsilon$ is < 0, $ lNOK < \gamma_{CAD}\cdot lCAD-\gamma_{SEK} \cdot lSEK$

i) Basic Strategy (for the first time $\epsilon$ > highC & $\epsilon$ < lowC)¶

  • Basic strategy is basic in that we only take position when it first cross the threshold line and do nothing when it stay above/below the higher/lower threshold.

  • At the first time $\epsilon$ < lowC $\Rightarrow$ Long $\frac{1}{p_{NOK}}$ unit of NOK, Short $\frac{\gamma_{SEK}}{p_{SEK}}$ unit of SEK, Long $\frac{\gamma_{CAD}}{p_{CAD}}$ CAD

  • AT the first time $\epsilon$ > highC $\Rightarrow$ Short $\frac{1}{p_{NOK}}$ unit of NOK, Long $\frac{\gamma_{SEK}}{p_{SEK}}$ unit of SEK, Short $\frac{\gamma_{CAD}}{p_{CAD}}$ CAD (after liquidating)

ii) Reinforcement Strategy¶

  • Reinforcement strategy takes position whenever satisfying the criteria and stay its position unless it crosses back to the threshold.
  • Whenever $\epsilon$ < lowC $\Rightarrow$ Long $\frac{1}{p_{NOK}}$ unit of NOK, Short $\frac{\gamma_{SEK}}{p_{SEK}}$ unit of SEK, Long $\frac{\gamma_{CAD}}{p_{CAD}}$ CAD
  • Whenever $\epsilon$ > highC $\Rightarrow$ Short $\frac{1}{p_{NOK}}$ unit of NOK, Long $\frac{\gamma_{SEK}}{p_{SEK}}$ unit of SEK, Short $\frac{\gamma_{CAD}}{p_{CAD}}$ CAD (after liquidating)

iii) Reinforce with limit on the number of open positions¶

  • This strategy takes position whenever satisfying the criteria and stay its position for limited number of time, not always as in (ii)
  • For certain number of times when $\epsilon$ < lowC $\Rightarrow$ Long $\frac{1}{p_{NOK}}$ unit of NOK, Short $\frac{\gamma_{SEK}}{p_{SEK}}$ unit of SEK, Long $\frac{\gamma_{CAD}}{p_{CAD}}$ CAD
  • For certain number of times when $\epsilon$ > highC $\Rightarrow$ Short $\frac{1}{p_{NOK}}$ unit of NOK, Long $\frac{\gamma_{SEK}}{p_{SEK}}$ unit of SEK, Short $\frac{\gamma_{CAD}}{p_{CAD}}$ CAD (after liquidating)

Inspect the time series plot of the $\epsilon$ as well as the histogram. Determine whether you prefer to select the threshold criteria between (1) mean-sd and (2) quantile based on the given information

The histogram and the fitted normal pdf clearly shows that the residual is not normally distributed. We can also try QQ plot

Try QQ Plot¶

Explain how the information in the time series plot and the histogram may be insufficient to decide highC and lowC.

It is insufficient in two ways.

1) By relying on the plot and histogram, we can't decide whether it is normally distributed or not. Instead, we can try two other common statistical tests that are QQ plot and Kolmogorov–Smirnov test as below

2) We can not guarantee stationarity (mean reverting) that we want to have in order to make pair trading work properly. Need to do ADF test for residuals

QQ plot shows that residual doesn't follows normal distribution.


The Kolmogorov–Smirnov tests
If a sample distribution fits a cumulative distribution function (CDF) of are referenced distribution. Null hypothesis for our sample is that the distribution is identical to the normal distribution. If p < .05 we can reject the null, and conclude our sample distribution is not identical to a normal distribution. In this case, we have p-value less than 0.05, I prefer to use the quantile one.

Let’s see what kind of profits this signal can generate. We write a simple backtester

  • buy 1 NOK, gamma_CAD unit CAD, and sell gamma_SEK unit SEK when spread is low
  • sell 1 NOK, gamma_CAD unit CAD, and buy gamma_SEK unit SEK when spread is high

Then calculate Profit & Loss of these trades.

In [25]:
# Define variables
gamma = results3.params

Position is taken the first time when

  • Buy Signal Generated at the first time $\epsilon$ < lowC after $\epsilon$ > highC

    • Long $\frac{1}{p_{NOK}}$ unit of NOK, Short $\frac{\gamma_{SEK}}{p_{SEK}}$ unit of SEK, Long $\frac{\gamma_{CAD}}{p_{CAD}}$ CAD

  • Sell Signal Generated at the first time $\epsilon$ > highC happens after $\epsilon$ < lowC

    • Short $\frac{1}{p_{NOK}}$ unit of NOK, Long $\frac{\gamma_{SEK}}{p_{SEK}}$ unit of SEK, Short $\frac{\gamma_{CAD}}{p_{CAD}}$ CAD (after liquidating)

Basic Trading Algorithm¶

In [33]:
# Trading Algorithm for Basic Strategy
# input x with quantile (ex) Basic([45,55])
def Basic (x):
    
    lowC = np.quantile(spread,x[0]*0.01)
    highC = np.quantile(spread,x[1]*0.01)
    
    low_ind = spread[spread<lowC].index
    high_ind = spread[spread>highC].index
    h = high_ind.min()
    l = low_ind.min()

    low_list = spread[spread<lowC].index.tolist()
    high_list = spread[spread>highC].index.tolist()
    
    trading_ind = np.r_[l].tolist()
    
    while True:
        if h > 2217 or l > 2217:
            break
        if h < l:
            if len(set(high_list).intersection(set(np.r_[(l+1):2218]))) == 0:
                break
            else:
                h = min(set(high_list).intersection(set(np.r_[(l+1):2218])))
                trading_ind.append(h)
        else:
            if len(set(low_list).intersection(set(np.r_[(h+1):2218]))) == 0:
                break
            else:
                l = min(set(low_list).intersection(set(np.r_[(h+1):2218])))
                trading_ind.append(l)
    money = 1
    signal = 1
    for i in range(len(trading_ind)-1):
            t1 = trading_ind[i]
            t2 = trading_ind[i+1]
            money += signal*(1/nok[t1]*(nok[t2]-nok[t1])
                        -gamma.CAD*(1/cad[t1])*(cad[t2]-cad[t1])
                            -gamma.SEK*(1/sek[t1])*(sek[t2]-sek[t1]))
            signal = -signal
    return money, signal, trading_ind

Reinforce Strategy¶

In [39]:
# Trading Algorithm for Basic Strategy
def Reinforce(x):
    
    lowC = np.quantile(spread,x[0]*0.01)
    highC = np.quantile(spread,x[1]*0.01)
    
    low_ind = spread[spread<lowC].index
    high_ind = spread[spread>highC].index
    h = high_ind.min()
    l = low_ind.min()

    low_list = spread[spread<lowC].index.tolist()
    high_list = spread[spread>highC].index.tolist()
    
    if h > l:
        trading_ind = np.r_[l,h].tolist()
        signal = -1
    else:
        trading_ind = np.r_[h,l].tolist()
        signal = 1
    
    while True:
        if h > 2217 or l > 2217:
            break
        if h < l:
            if len(set(high_list).intersection(set(np.r_[(l+1):2218]))) == 0:
                break
            else:
                h =min(set(high_list).intersection(set(np.r_[(l+1):2218])))
                trading_ind.append(h)
        else:
            if len(set(low_list).intersection(set(np.r_[(h+1):2218]))) == 0:
                break
            else:
                l =min(set(low_list).intersection(set(np.r_[(h+1):2218])))
                trading_ind.append(l)
                
    money = 1
    signal = -1
    hold_ind = 0
    trading_points = list()
    
    for i in range(len(trading_ind)-1):
        t1 = trading_ind[i]
        t2 = trading_ind[i+1]
        if signal > 0:
            trading_duration = set(low_list).intersection(set(np.r_[t1:t2-1]))
            for j in trading_duration:
                money += signal*(1/nok[j]*(nok[t2]-nok[j])
                            -gamma.CAD*(1/cad[j])*(cad[t2]-cad[j])
                                 -gamma.SEK*(1/sek[j])*(sek[t2]-sek[j]))
            trading_points.append(trading_duration)
        else:
            trading_duration = set(high_list).intersection(set(np.r_[t1:t2-1]))
            for j in trading_duration:
                money += signal*(1/nok[j]*(nok[t2]-nok[j])
                        -gamma.CAD*(1/cad[j])*(cad[t2]-cad[j])
                            -gamma.SEK*(1/sek[j])*(sek[t2]-sek[j]))
            trading_points.append(trading_duration)
            hold_ind += len(trading_duration)
        signal = -signal
    return money, signal, trading_points, hold_ind
